%S A396240 3,1,3,3,3,3,3,5,2,2,5,3,3,5,1,2,2,5,3,2,5,5,7,3,3,3,3,3,9,9,5,2,3,3,
%T A396240 2,1,5,5,1,2,3,3,3,3,7,1,2,3,3,5,2,3,4,1,1,2,2,5,3,3,6,9,3,3,9,5,4,3,
%U A396240 3,5,7,7,1,5,5,7,3,3,9,3,3,3,2,5,5,7,3,3,3,2
%N A396240 Denominator of r(n) = (prime(n+2) - 2*prime(n+1) + prime(n)) / (prime(n+2) - prime(n)).
%C A396240 (See A396239 Numerator)
%C A396240 r(n) is the second difference of the primes (A036263(n)) divided by the second sum (A031131(n)); equivalently r(n) = (g_next - g_prev)/(g_next + g_prev), where g_prev and g_next are the prime gaps on either side of prime(n+1). -1 < r(n) < 1 for all n, since |g_next - g_prev| < g_next + g_prev for positive gaps; the bounds +-1 are never attained. (Provable.)
%C A396240 r(n) = 0 if and only if prime(n+1) is a balanced prime (A006562), i.e. g_prev = g_next. (Provable.) Two primes with equal second difference (A036263) need not have equal r(n), so r(n) distinguishes primes more finely than A036263 alone.
%C A396240 The author calls r(n) the "second ratio" of a prime.
%H A396240 Edward Bernstein, <a href="/A396240/b396240.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A396240 Edward Bernstein, <a href="https://fractal-core.com/drift">Drift of r(n) across prime neighborhood scales</a>, an interactive chart of how the distribution of r(n) shifts as the primes grow.
%F A396240 a(n) = denominator(A036263(n) / A031131(n)).
%F A396240 a(n) = A031131(n) / gcd(A036263(n), A031131(n)).
%e A396240 n=1: 1/3, so a(1) = 3.
%e A396240 n=2: 0/1, so a(2) = 1.
%e A396240 n=9: -1/2, so a(9) = 2.
%p A396240 seq(denom((ithprime(n+2)-2*ithprime(n+1)+ithprime(n))/(ithprime(n+2)-ithprime(n))), n=1..70);
%t A396240 a[n_] := Denominator[(Prime[n+2] - 2 Prime[n+1] + Prime[n])/(Prime[n+2] - Prime[n])]; Array[a, 70]
%o A396240 (PARI) a(n) = my(p=prime(n), q=prime(n+1), r=prime(n+2)); denominator((r-2*q+p)/(r-p));
%Y A396240 Cf. A396239 (numerators), A036263, A031131, A001223, A006562.
%K A396240 nonn,frac,easy,new
%O A396240 1,1
%A A396240 _Edward Bernstein_, May 19 2026
